'''Tajikarao Shrine''' (たぢからおじんじゃ) is a shrine located in {{ill|Tateyama City|ja|館山市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
== History == According to tradition, the shrine was first established in the 1st year of Emperor Jimmu ({{ill|660 BCE|ja|紀元前660th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) by the {{ill|Inbe clan|ja|忌部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. In the {{ill|Tenshō era|ja|天正|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)|lt=Tenshō Era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 12 ({{ill|1584|ja|1584th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}}), the shrine building was reconstructed with contributions from {{ill|Satomi Yoshiyori|ja|里見義頼|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the shrine was referred to as Ōi Daimyōjin and was revered by the {{ill|Satomi clan|ja|里見氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and later by the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It was granted protected shrine lands.
== Major Rituals == * September - Saturday and Sunday before {{ill|Respect for the Aged Day|ja|敬老の日|qq=draft|qq=draft}}: Awa Kuni no Miyatsukomatsuri (Yawata no Matsuri, "Yawata Festival") * October 9 - Annual Grand Festival The Awa Kuni no Miyatsukomatsuri is the festival of {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachiman Shrine|ja|鶴谷八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the former provincial shrine of Awa Province, where a mikoshi (portable shrine) from this shrine participates.
