'''Tajikarao Shrine''' (たぢからおじんじゃ) is a shrine located in [[:en:Tateyama, Chiba|Tateyama City]], [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]].
== History == According to tradition, the shrine was first established in the 1st year of Emperor Jimmu ([[:en:660 BC|660 BCE]]) by the [[:en:Inbe clan|Inbe clan]]. In the [[:en:Tenshō (Momoyama period)|Tenshō Era]] 12 ([[:en:1584|1584]]), the shrine building was reconstructed with contributions from {{ill|Satomi Yoshiyori|ja|里見義頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Satomi Yoshiyori|qq=}}. During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the shrine was referred to as Ōi Daimyōjin and was revered by the [[:en:Satomi clan|Satomi clan]] and later by the {{ill|Tokugawa shogunate|ja|Tokugawa shogunate|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa shogunate|qq=}}. It was granted protected shrine lands.
== Major Rituals == * September - Saturday and Sunday before [[:en:Respect for the Aged Day|Respect for the Aged Day]]: Awa Kuni no Miyatsukomatsuri (Yawata no Matsuri, "Yawata Festival") * October 9 - Annual Grand Festival The Awa Kuni no Miyatsukomatsuri is the festival of {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|lt=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|lt=Tsurugaoka Hachiman Shrine|ja|鶴谷八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsurugaoka Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}, the former provincial shrine of Awa Province, where a mikoshi (portable shrine) from this shrine participates.
== Cultural Properties == * **Main Hall** - {{ill|List of Tangible Cultural Properties of Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県指定文化財一覧#建造物|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/List of Tangible Cultural Properties of Chiba Prefecture|qq=}} (Tangible Cultural Property of Chiba Prefecture) ** Constructed in the [[:en:Tenshō (Momoyama period)|Tenshō Era]] 12 ([[:en:1584|1584]]) as indicated by the ridge tag. Damaged in the {{ill|Genroku Earthquake|ja|元禄大地震|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genroku Earthquake|qq=}} ([[:en:1703|1703]]) and reconstructed during the [[:en:Hōei|Hōei era]] ([[:en:1704|1704]]–[[:en:1710|1710]]). Features architectural styles from the [[:en:Azuchi–Momoyama period|Azuchi–Momoyama period]], such as kaerumata (frog-leg struts) and eaves curvature, alongside elements characteristic of the mid-[[:en:Edo period|Edo period]]. ([http://furusato.mbit.or.jp/modules/dbx/?op=story&storyid=610 Source]) * **Great Cedar Tree** - {{ill|List of Natural Monuments of Tateyama City|ja|館山市指定文化財一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/List of Natural Monuments of Tateyama City|qq=}} (Natural Monument of Tateyama City) [[File:手力雄神社・鳥居.jpg|thumb|Tajikarao Shrine Torii Gate]]
